# JobHunter AI — Cursor Rules

You are building JobHunter AI, a self-hosted job scraping app. Read PROJECT.md first for full context. Follow these rules in every phase.

## Identity

This is a LOCAL-FIRST app that runs on someone's laptop. Not a SaaS. Not a cloud deployment. Everything runs with `python run.py`. The user opens localhost:8000 in their browser and uses a dashboard to configure and control the agent. The browser-use agent opens a real Chrome window to scrape job sites.

## Tech Stack (locked)

- Python 3.11+
- FastAPI for backend (async)
- Jinja2 for HTML templates (server-side rendered)
- Vanilla HTML + CSS + JS for frontend (NO React, NO build step, NO npm)
- browser-use library for AI browser agent
- Playwright for browser automation (installed via `playwright install chromium`)
- Gemini 2.0 Flash as default LLM (user can switch to GPT-4o-mini, Claude, Ollama)
- SQLite for database (via aiosqlite for async)
- openpyxl for Excel generation
- smtplib for email (Gmail SMTP)
- APScheduler for recurring runs
- SSE (Server-Sent Events) for live status updates to dashboard
- python-dotenv for environment variables

Do NOT introduce any technology not listed here. No Redis. No PostgreSQL. No Celery. No WebSockets. No Docker requirement.

## Python Code Rules

- snake_case for everything: files, functions, variables, database columns
- Type hints on all function signatures
- Pydantic models for all API request/response schemas
- Async functions everywhere in FastAPI routes and database operations
- Max 200 lines per file. Split if longer.
- Max 30 lines per function. Extract helpers if longer.
- No global mutable state. Pass dependencies through function arguments or FastAPI Depends().
- All database operations go through db.py. No raw SQL in route handlers.
- All browser-use agent tasks go in agents/ directory. One file per source.
- Use logging module, not print(). Logger name = module name.
- Every function that can fail gets try/except with meaningful error messages.
- No hardcoded strings for config values. Everything comes from db config or .env.

## Frontend Rules

- Single HTML file (index.html) served by Jinja2
- Single CSS file (style.css) in static/
- Single JS file (app.js) in static/
- NO CSS frameworks. Write vanilla CSS. Clean, modern, minimal.
- NO JS frameworks. Vanilla JS with fetch() for API calls.
- Mobile-friendly layout (flexbox, max-width containers)
- Dark theme by default with a clean, professional look
- All user interactions go through the REST API. No server-side form submissions.
- SSE via EventSource for live status updates during agent runs.
- Forms use JS event handlers, NOT HTML form submissions.

## API Rules

- All endpoints prefixed with /api/
- Response shapes:
  - Success single: { "data": { ... } }
  - Success list: { "data": [...], "count": N }
  - Error: { "detail": "message" }
- Use proper HTTP status codes (200, 201, 400, 404, 500)
- Validate all inputs with Pydantic
- Return JSON for all API endpoints

## Database Rules

- SQLite only. File at data/jobs.db.
- Use aiosqlite for async access.
- All schema creation in db.py init_db() function.
- URL is the dedup key for jobs. UNIQUE constraint on jobs.url.
- Config is a single row (id=1) updated in place.
- Use parameterized queries. Never format SQL strings.
- Always use context managers for connections.

## Agent Rules

- Each source (LinkedIn, Indeed, YC, career pages) is a separate file in agents/.
- orchestrator.py coordinates all agents and reports status.
- Agent tasks are defined as plain-English instructions passed to browser-use.
- The agent LLM provider is configurable: gemini (default), openai, anthropic, ollama.
- Agent must use the user's real Chrome profile so logged-in sessions (LinkedIn) persist.
- Agent runs in a background asyncio task, not blocking the FastAPI server.
- Status updates are pushed to a queue that the SSE endpoint reads from.
- Each agent function returns a list of dicts: [{"title": str, "company": str, "url": str}]
- If an agent fails (CAPTCHA, timeout, crash), log the error, skip that source, continue with others.

## File Naming

- Python files: snake_case.py
- Templates: snake_case.html
- Static: snake_case.css, snake_case.js
- Docs: UPPER_CASE.md

## Git Rules

- Commit after every working feature
- Format: type: short description
- Types: feat, fix, docs, refactor, chore
- Work on main branch. No branch overhead.
- Never commit: .env, __pycache__, data/*.db, output/*.xlsx, .DS_Store

## Error Handling

- Agent failures: log error, skip source, continue run, report in status
- Email failures: log error, save Excel locally, report in status
- Database failures: crash with clear error message (unrecoverable)
- API validation: return 400 with detail message
- Unexpected errors: return 500, log full traceback

## Non-Negotiable

- PROJECT.md is the source of truth for what to build
- Phase specs define scope. Do not add features not in the current phase.
- Zero code from AI in phase specs. You (Cursor) write all implementation.
- No Docker. No build steps. pip install + python run.py = working app.
- The browser must be VISIBLE by default (headless: false). Users need to see it and solve CAPTCHAs.
- Deduplication via URL uniqueness in SQLite. Never show the same job twice.
- Email only sends when new jobs > 0.
